    "K=3 degree sweep: d=2 -> 10x, d=4 -> 8.43x.  At K=3 (8-outcome distribution) d=4 still helps but the gain is smaller (1.6x reduction vs 1.9x at K=2).  The depth cost (+54 percent) almost cancels the polynomial-accuracy gain.",
    "The depth-noise trade-off: at depth ~200-300, doubling the depth roughly doubles the gate-decoherence noise.  The QSVT signal gain from sharper thresholding is bounded by the polynomial approximation; once the polynomial is sharp enough to resolve the discrete outcomes, more phases just add decoherence.",
    "Total improvement vs K=17 baseline: depth 1285 -> 228 (5.6x reduction), rel err 620x -> 4.25x (146x improvement).  K=2 d=4 10k shots is the global best; further K reduction (K=1) or degree tuning (d=3 or d=5) might find marginal gains but the noise floor is now the dominant error source."
